The main problem with anti tamper labels that are commercially purchased is
that the bad guys can buy them from the same suppliers you do.   When a
single enclosure goes for $15K a pop, it's awfully tempting for a technician
who makes $15/hour to swap the contents of a good part with a bad one, make
a false claim that the part is defective, and walk away with $15K.    $15K
buys a lot of equipment to replace anti-tamper labels.

Someone in one of these groups in a similar thread had the nearly brilliant
idea to use the serial numbers on printed currency for the anti-tamper.
We like that idea a lot, because any modern currency uses multiple features
that are difficult to replicate and defeat.   It's highly unlikely that
someone making $15/hour is going to have the time, skill, and talent to
defeat the underlying patterns printed on the currency, let alone invest in
reprinting specific serial numbers on a one-off basis.

The main problem now is how to we ensure the paper is melted into the sheet
metal such that it cannot just be soaked in solvent and cleanly lifted off
in a single piece.  The glue has to be not only aggressive at binding, but
aggressive at dissolving the paper in a way that makes it easy to tear/rip
and impossible to just peal off cleanly.

--
